# All Paths From Source to Target - LeetCode Solution

## Problem Statement

**LeetCode Problem #797**: [All Paths From Source to Target](https://leetcode.com/problems/all-paths-from-source-to-target/)

Given a directed acyclic graph (**DAG**) of `n` nodes labeled from `0` to `n-1`, find **all possible paths** from node `0` to node `n-1`.

The graph is given as an adjacency list where `graph[i]` is a list of all nodes you can visit from node `i`.

##  Approach
This solution uses Breadth-First Search (BFS) to find all paths from source (0) to target (n-1).
Key Points:

We treat each path as a list of nodes.
Use a Queue to perform BFS, storing the entire path so far.
When we reach the target node, we add the complete path to the result.
Since it's a DAG (no cycles), we don't need to track visited nodes.

## Time Complexity

O(N × 2^E) in worst case (where N is nodes and E is edges), because we may explore all possible paths.

## Space Complexity

O(N × 2^E) — due to storing all paths in the queue and result.
//-------------------------------------------------------------graph(BFS)--------------------------------------------------------------//
class Solution {
    public List<List<Integer>> allPathsSourceTarget(int[][] graph) {
        int n = graph.length;
         int source = 0;
        int target = n-1;
        
        List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
        Queue<List<Integer>> queue = new LinkedList<>();

        List<Integer> temp = new ArrayList<>();
        temp.add(source);
        queue.offer(temp);

        while(!queue.isEmpty()){
            List<Integer> currPath = queue.poll();

            int lastNode = currPath.get(currPath.size() - 1);

            if(lastNode == target){
                result.add(currPath);
            }
            else{
                for(int v: graph[lastNode]){
                    List<Integer> newPath = new ArrayList<>(currPath);
                    newPath.add(v);
                    queue.offer(newPath);
                }
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
